in your books not?

00:57:17.860 --> 00:57:23.410
- Well, there are Calvinists
that deserve that reputation.

00:57:23.410 --> 00:57:24.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:24.790 --> 00:57:26.260
What can I say?

00:57:26.260 --> 00:57:29.830
I mean, I think part of
my fascination with Calvin

00:57:29.830 --> 00:57:31.780
is resurrection.

00:57:31.780 --> 00:57:37.060
I'm trying to excavate him from
this burial under the worst

00:57:37.060 --> 00:57:41.830
implications that people
have drawn from his writing.

00:57:41.830 --> 00:57:48.730
Every major theologian,
including Ignatius Loyola,

00:57:48.730 --> 00:57:51.790
has said, yes, there
is predestination.

00:57:51.790 --> 00:57:54.400
The only two who
don't agree with this

00:57:54.400 --> 00:57:56.590
is [? Chrysostom ?]
and John Wesley.

00:57:56.590 --> 00:58:01.340
So how did it get
pinned on Calvin?

00:58:01.340 --> 00:58:02.170
Polemic.

00:58:02.170 --> 00:58:04.870
I think he had the
problem of being

00:58:04.870 --> 00:58:10.810
the most effective polemicist,
the most effective theoretician

00:58:10.810 --> 00:58:11.650
of his period.

00:58:11.650 --> 00:58:17.710
And therefore, he took the
brunt of a lot of controversy.

00:58:17.710 --> 00:58:19.930
That's a very complex
question I've brought up,

00:58:19.930 --> 00:58:23.620
but nevertheless, things like
that that are artificially

00:58:23.620 --> 00:58:25.900
associated with him as
if other people had not

00:58:25.900 --> 00:58:29.180
come to the same conclusion.

00:58:29.180 --> 00:58:32.036
And then there are just
inexcusable Calvinists.

00:58:32.036 --> 00:58:33.524
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:38.290
- Hi, I'm Heather.

00:58:38.290 --> 00:58:40.900
Happy to be here [INAUDIBLE]
I was [? thinking ?] when

00:58:40.900 --> 00:58:43.630
you were talking about in
the absence of a caring God,

00:58:43.630 --> 00:58:46.090
is our suffering meaningful.

00:58:46.090 --> 00:58:48.910
And just a thought, so
I won't go on too long.

00:58:48.910 --> 00:58:51.700
But I was thinking, for me as
a humanist, I feel like my job

00:58:51.700 --> 00:58:54.190
as a human being is to
watch other people suffering

00:58:54.190 --> 00:58:56.110
with at least watchful
concern and caring,

00:58:56.110 --> 00:58:58.316
that that's what people
do for each other.

00:58:58.316 --> 00:59:00.190
And then I think, as a
reader, the characters

00:59:00.190 --> 00:59:01.420
I love the most
and the writers I

00:59:01.420 --> 00:59:04.090
love the most, I feel like those
characters are sitting with me,

00:59:04.090 --> 00:59:07.450
that they can sit and keep
me company in my suffering

00:59:07.450 --> 00:59:08.549
without a God being here.

00:59:08.549 --> 00:59:10.840
So I was just wondering what
you thought about humanism

00:59:10.840 --> 00:59:13.000
as a way of approaching
giving meaning

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:18.460
to suffering even if I don't
feel a caring God is up there.

00:59:18.460 --> 00:59:21.800
- Well, that makes suffering
a different kind of problem,

00:59:21.800 --> 00:59:24.370
certainly.

00:59:24.370 --> 00:59:31.840
I think that human freedom
is real in the sense

00:59:31.840 --> 00:59:36.130
that we, from moment to moment,
have the option of dealing with

00:59:36.130 --> 00:59:41.410
people with the degree of
respect that they yearn for.

00:59:41.410 --> 00:59:44.170
A lot of suffering, I
think, is not visible.

00:59:44.170 --> 00:59:48.100
I think that a huge
source of suffering

00:59:48.100 --> 00:59:52.936
is the rationing of
respect that we engage in.

00:59:52.936 --> 00:59:54.880
In other words, I
think that we are

00:59:54.880 --> 00:59:58.900
given the real
problem of dealing

00:59:58.900 --> 01:00:06.290
with the sad burden of human
sensitivity in all its forms,

01:00:06.290 --> 01:00:11.500
and that the
question is actually,

01:00:11.500 --> 01:00:17.260
are we going to
respond from the soul?

01:00:17.260 --> 01:00:23.170
And that's one of the
existential questions

01:00:23.170 --> 01:00:27.670
that we are burdened with or
dignified by as human beings.

