01:01:07.360 --> 01:01:09.280
and I think you
alluded to it when

01:01:09.280 --> 01:01:14.020
you talked about authorial
respect for characters.

01:01:14.020 --> 01:01:18.070
And that was there
was clearly something,

01:01:18.070 --> 01:01:20.440
quote, unquote,
"wrong" with Sylvie--

01:01:20.440 --> 01:01:22.100
or mental illness.

01:01:22.100 --> 01:01:24.340
I don't know what
you want to call it.

01:01:24.340 --> 01:01:30.490
But the respect accorded
her and the girls

01:01:30.490 --> 01:01:36.520
and the sad history of the
family was very moving.

01:01:36.520 --> 01:01:42.070
And I don't know if you had
encountered in your life

01:01:42.070 --> 01:01:44.650
or in your town or
whatever, but what

01:01:44.650 --> 01:01:53.080
made you just have such a much
larger vision of these people

01:01:53.080 --> 01:01:58.560
than a lot of
writers might have.

01:01:58.560 --> 01:02:02.410
- Well, I was talking
earlier about how,

01:02:02.410 --> 01:02:04.680
reading contemporary
fiction at the time,

01:02:04.680 --> 01:02:08.580
I couldn't find characters
that seemed real to me

01:02:08.580 --> 01:02:10.560
that were complex enough.

01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:16.170
And so my solution was to
do a kind of Cubist portrait

01:02:16.170 --> 01:02:18.690
where Ruth--

01:02:18.690 --> 01:02:23.130
in my mind, Ruth is one
profile, and Lucille is another,

01:02:23.130 --> 01:02:24.760
and [? Sophie ?] is another.

01:02:24.760 --> 01:02:26.550
It's Cubist.

01:02:26.550 --> 01:02:31.080
But in any case, I
consider them to be--

01:02:31.080 --> 01:02:35.040
I mean, I think everyone lives
not only with the choices we

01:02:35.040 --> 01:02:37.940
have made, but with the
choices we have not made,

01:02:37.940 --> 01:02:40.200
with the kind of
yearnings that we

01:02:40.200 --> 01:02:43.470
have felt we had to suppress.

01:02:43.470 --> 01:02:45.630
Where I lived, I think
one of the yearnings,

01:02:45.630 --> 01:02:47.850
since there was just
wilderness all around us,

01:02:47.850 --> 01:02:51.600
was that you could just
take off and just disappear

01:02:51.600 --> 01:02:54.870
into nature in some way.

01:02:54.870 --> 01:03:00.510
So I was rewarded, when I
tried to make, by my lights,

01:03:00.510 --> 01:03:02.940
one character
richer, by the fact

01:03:02.940 --> 01:03:05.220
that it seemed to make
all the characters richer,

01:03:05.220 --> 01:03:08.220
in my experience.

01:03:08.220 --> 01:03:10.830
So that's what was
happening there.

01:03:14.521 --> 01:03:15.020
- Hi.

01:03:15.020 --> 01:03:17.480
My name is [INAUDIBLE],, and
I'm a senior at the college

01:03:17.480 --> 01:03:19.890
studying sociology.

01:03:19.890 --> 01:03:20.860
So I love your fiction.

01:03:20.860 --> 01:03:22.670
I'm a huge fan of your
fiction, but I also

01:03:22.670 --> 01:03:25.580
love your essay collections,
The Death of Adam

01:03:25.580 --> 01:03:29.630
and When I Was a
Child I Read Books.

01:03:29.630 --> 01:03:34.430
And I was really struck by
the ideas of Old Testament

01:03:34.430 --> 01:03:39.020
traditions and liberality and,
as you've been talking about,

01:03:39.020 --> 01:03:41.270
restoration and resurrection.

01:03:41.270 --> 01:03:43.580
And it resonated
with me not only

01:03:43.580 --> 01:03:45.530
because you were very
convincing, but also

01:03:45.530 --> 01:03:48.920
because of my own Protestant
traditions growing up.

01:03:48.920 --> 01:03:51.530
But I wanted to ask
whether your ideas

01:03:51.530 --> 01:03:55.700
on social justice, which have
been really compelling because

01:03:55.700 --> 01:03:58.820
of this prophetic, religious
fire that you have,

01:03:58.820 --> 01:04:02.990
whether religious thinking
is a foundational premise

01:04:02.990 --> 01:04:06.410
for these social justice
ideas, or just the lens

01:04:06.410 --> 01:04:07.950
through which you
look at issues.

01:04:07.950 --> 01:04:12.440
So is God or religious
thinking a necessary condition

01:04:12.440 --> 01:04:16.250
of your ideas, or is it
just one of many lenses

01:04:16.250 --> 01:04:18.410
that you can have or
that any person can

01:04:18.410 --> 01:04:21.110
have looking through
it, as a secular lens,

01:04:21.110 --> 01:04:24.240
for instance, and reaching
the same conclusion?

01:04:24.240 --> 01:04:25.990
- Yes, it's an
interesting question.

01:04:25.990 --> 01:04:30.450
I think that there's a tendency
to think of religion as being

01:04:30.450 --> 01:04:32.520
doctrinal and formulated.

01:04:32.520 --> 01:04:34.470
I think there are lots
of people who would not

01:04:34.470 --> 01:04:36.210
think of themselves
as religious,

01:04:36.210 --> 01:04:38.910
but nevertheless, they
look at another human being

01:04:38.910 --> 01:04:42.210
and they say, this is sacred.

01:04:42.210 --> 01:04:44.670
We ought not to allow
this to happen--

01:04:44.670 --> 01:04:48.390
a crowded prison, or any
of the infinite number

01:04:48.390 --> 01:04:50.790
of things that we see.

01:04:50.790 --> 01:04:54.720
I think that if you have an
intuition of the sanctity

01:04:54.720 --> 01:04:58.870
of a human being so that
you want to give them

01:04:58.870 --> 01:05:03.310
dignity and the
possibility of living out

01:05:03.310 --> 01:05:05.870
their lives by their
lives and so on,

01:05:05.870 --> 01:05:08.710
that is basically a
religious impulse.

01:05:08.710 --> 01:05:15.130
It's just non-doctrinal,
non-denominational.

01:05:15.130 --> 01:05:18.000
- But it could-- just to leap
in, but it could be there's no

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:21.010
reason why it needs to
be grounded necessarily

01:05:21.010 --> 01:05:23.985
in the notion of the divine.

01:05:23.985 --> 01:05:24.610
- I don't know.

01:05:24.610 --> 01:05:27.220
I mean, I think that you
proceed from a different set

01:05:27.220 --> 01:05:29.230
of assumptions that I do.

01:05:29.230 --> 01:05:31.870
I think that if you see
the sacred in anything,

01:05:31.870 --> 01:05:34.390
that is an intuition
of the divine.

01:05:34.390 --> 01:05:37.510
It doesn't matter if
it's quantum physics

01:05:37.510 --> 01:05:41.700
or your next-door neighbor.

01:05:41.700 --> 01:05:44.450
- Thank you.

01:05:44.450 --> 01:05:45.364
- Hi.

01:05:45.364 --> 01:05:46.780
I was wondering
if you could speak

01:05:46.780 --> 01:05:48.280
a little bit about
your experience

01:05:48.280 --> 01:05:50.500
as a writing
instructor, what you've

01:05:50.500 --> 01:05:53.620
observed in the classroom, the
different mistakes students

01:05:53.620 --> 01:05:57.760
have made, promising
aspects of what's emerging

01:05:57.760 --> 01:06:00.460
from writing programs today.

01:06:00.460 --> 01:06:04.300
- Oh, a great deal is
emerging now, a great deal.

01:06:04.300 --> 01:06:07.330
I see a lot of students
making the mistake that I did,

01:06:07.330 --> 01:06:11.230
which is the idea that you can
look at what is being written

01:06:11.230 --> 01:06:13.240
in your moment and
feeling as though you have

01:06:13.240 --> 01:06:16.230
some obligation
to it or as if you

01:06:16.230 --> 01:06:18.430
will fall into a stream
of the publishable

01:06:18.430 --> 01:06:20.400
or something like that.

01:06:20.400 --> 01:06:23.950
And, I mean, if you're
trying to do that,

01:06:23.950 --> 01:06:28.210
then you're making yourself
second-rate, in effect.

01:06:28.210 --> 01:06:30.490
It's incredibly difficult
to do, but people

01:06:30.490 --> 01:06:34.010
have to find their own voices,
as everybody tells you,

01:06:34.010 --> 01:06:37.330
but they tell you the truth.

01:06:37.330 --> 01:06:40.116
The workshop, at
the moment, it's

01:06:40.116 --> 01:06:41.740
going through an
interesting transition

01:06:41.740 --> 01:06:47.260
because finally, we have
a diversity of students.

01:06:47.260 --> 01:06:49.900
For such a long
time, people will not

01:06:49.900 --> 01:06:51.580
apply to come to
Iowa because it's

01:06:51.580 --> 01:06:53.530
Iowa, which is a lovely state.

01:06:53.530 --> 01:06:54.700
I mean, it's just a--

01:06:54.700 --> 01:06:57.070
but anyway, this has ended now.

01:06:57.070 --> 01:07:01.150
So we're getting a lot of kids
that are first generation, kids

01:07:01.150 --> 01:07:03.010
from the Caribbean, and so on.

01:07:03.010 --> 01:07:08.080
And people like that
have the advantage

01:07:08.080 --> 01:07:12.140
of making a case for the
world they come from.

01:07:12.140 --> 01:07:16.540
And so they're very attentive
to the kind of beautiful details

01:07:16.540 --> 01:07:25.100
of life that most of us only
notice when you stop and think,

01:07:25.100 --> 01:07:27.940
well, this is a beautiful,
sunlit day here,

01:07:27.940 --> 01:07:31.840
even in the middle
of the Middle West.

01:07:31.840 --> 01:07:34.780
So there's a kind of
richness that is coming in,

01:07:34.780 --> 01:07:37.470
and an attentiveness to detail--

01:07:37.470 --> 01:07:40.030
you're great on detail--

01:07:40.030 --> 01:07:42.610
that is a tremendous
[? balloon. ?]

01:07:42.610 --> 01:07:45.280
We're seeing a lot
of interesting stuff.

01:07:45.280 --> 01:07:47.519
It diversifies the voices.

01:07:47.519 --> 01:07:49.810
It makes everybody more
conscious of what they're there

01:07:49.810 --> 01:07:50.660
to do.

01:07:50.660 --> 01:07:52.210
It's a very good thing.

01:07:54.870 --> 01:07:56.240
- Hi, my name is Abigail.

01:07:56.240 --> 01:07:59.600
And I was curious about
the role of reading.

01:07:59.600 --> 01:08:01.400
So it seemed as
though you articulated

01:08:01.400 --> 01:08:05.630
that you wanted to read widely
before returning to fiction,

01:08:05.630 --> 01:08:09.620
or it seemed somehow necessary
to develop a new sense of self

01:08:09.620 --> 01:08:10.460
as a writer.

01:08:10.460 --> 01:08:13.780
But it didn't seem like you had
that same feeling about writing

01:08:13.780 --> 01:08:15.560
nonfiction in essays.

01:08:15.560 --> 01:08:18.920
And I'm wondering about the role
of that kind of wide reading

01:08:18.920 --> 01:08:20.840
in both of those
voices, and also

01:08:20.840 --> 01:08:23.660
whether there's a different
sort of sense of position

01:08:23.660 --> 01:08:26.390
that comes when you write
nonfiction and fiction

01:08:26.390 --> 01:08:29.540
and how voice differs there.

01:08:29.540 --> 01:08:33.740
- Well, my essays,
they're usually lectures.

01:08:33.740 --> 01:08:36.979
And they're usually very much
as I delivered the lecture.

01:08:36.979 --> 01:08:39.290
And what they usually
are, I'm usually

01:08:39.290 --> 01:08:43.160
speaking to a college
or sometimes a church.

01:08:43.160 --> 01:08:46.760
They're little
screams of surprise.

01:08:46.760 --> 01:08:48.620
This is what you've
been led to believe.

01:08:48.620 --> 01:08:51.170
This is not true.

01:08:51.170 --> 01:08:54.080
And it's based on some
book I've been reading

01:08:54.080 --> 01:08:56.479
or some literature
I've been reading.

01:08:56.479 --> 01:09:03.500
And so the essays, up
until very recently--

01:09:03.500 --> 01:09:05.600
and perhaps recently also--

01:09:05.600 --> 01:09:08.840
are rooted directly in
my going back and looking

01:09:08.840 --> 01:09:11.720
at things that,
frankly, were things

01:09:11.720 --> 01:09:13.200
that were misrepresented to me.

01:09:16.329 --> 01:09:18.010
- Hi, my name is John.

01:09:18.010 --> 01:09:22.630
My question has to do with the
sense of religiosity or faith

01:09:22.630 --> 01:09:27.010
or kind of a belief in a
divine or something mysterious.

01:09:27.010 --> 01:09:28.870
I'm curious to know--
and this is something

01:09:28.870 --> 01:09:30.994
that I had experienced when
I was in college, too--

01:09:30.994 --> 01:09:34.479
whether it comes from a kind
of intellection or thinking,

01:09:34.479 --> 01:09:36.939
or it comes from
experience, or it

01:09:36.939 --> 01:09:41.410
comes from experience
that is kind of everyday

01:09:41.410 --> 01:09:46.450
and really not through
kind of a logical faculty.

01:09:46.450 --> 01:09:51.830
Where do you see that situated
within our mind and soul

01:09:51.830 --> 01:09:53.470
and in other parts of our body?

01:09:56.080 --> 01:09:59.530
- I think I have a more sort
of holistic sense of thinking.

01:09:59.530 --> 01:10:02.500
I mean, some of the craziest
writing in the world

01:10:02.500 --> 01:10:05.800
is writing that has taken
itself to be severely logical.

01:10:08.730 --> 01:10:16.300
And I think that experience, if
you're functioning attentively,

01:10:16.300 --> 01:10:19.360
experience feeds so directly
into every other aspect

01:10:19.360 --> 01:10:23.230
of your thinking and in
your dreams and so on.

01:10:23.230 --> 01:10:28.600
I think that if you isolate
something like intellection,

01:10:28.600 --> 01:10:32.260
you are robbing it of its
primary resources, which

01:10:32.260 --> 01:10:34.870
are all the other things
that you have named that also

01:10:34.870 --> 01:10:38.021
come into the experience.

01:10:38.021 --> 01:10:44.170
I think that we
are, for one thing,

01:10:44.170 --> 01:10:48.310
acculturated to exclude
from our thinking

01:10:48.310 --> 01:10:55.540
what we take to be imaginative,
as if imagination didn't

01:10:55.540 --> 01:10:59.380
discover a thousand things that
science has adopted, and so on.

01:11:03.280 --> 01:11:06.370
Also, I think we
live in a time when

01:11:06.370 --> 01:11:10.090
the notion of what religion
is is strange enough

01:11:10.090 --> 01:11:13.740
to drive people away
from it because it's

01:11:13.740 --> 01:11:17.110
settled so strangely
in a great many minds.

01:11:20.740 --> 01:11:23.560
It tends to be a claim
that you make for yourself

01:11:23.560 --> 01:11:26.440
rather than an obligation
you feel for yourself,

01:11:26.440 --> 01:11:29.440
that sort of thing.

01:11:29.440 --> 01:11:31.960
I think that if you just
sort of relax and think,

01:11:31.960 --> 01:11:34.780
my mind is my mind, and
it's so interesting,

01:11:34.780 --> 01:11:36.040
and here I am with it.

01:11:36.040 --> 01:11:40.540
And I will watch it live,
and it will watch me live--

01:11:40.540 --> 01:11:43.990
I always start out
telling my students

01:11:43.990 --> 01:11:46.840
that the human brain is the
most complex object known

01:11:46.840 --> 01:11:49.960
to exist in the universe,
which is simply true.

01:11:49.960 --> 01:11:51.650
You can read it in
Scientific American.

01:11:51.650 --> 01:11:53.910
[LAUGHTER]

01:11:53.910 --> 01:11:59.260
But if you think about that,
that every skull in this room

01:11:59.260 --> 01:12:06.454
has, in it, this primary object
of cosmic life, then you think,

01:12:06.454 --> 01:12:07.120
well, I have it.

01:12:07.120 --> 01:12:09.700
Now what do I do with it?

01:12:09.700 --> 01:12:11.440
Or what does it
do with me I think

01:12:11.440 --> 01:12:13.970
is a more important question.

01:12:13.970 --> 01:12:17.590
I think that you shouldn't
be passive in relation to it,

01:12:17.590 --> 01:12:22.060
and you shouldn't try to do the
procrustean thing of making it

01:12:22.060 --> 01:12:26.260
into something that is
useful to a industry

01:12:26.260 --> 01:12:30.760
rather than being the
unbelievable cosmic privilege

01:12:30.760 --> 01:12:35.310
of having that brain, that mind.

01:12:35.310 --> 01:12:36.980
- May I ask a
follow-up question?

01:12:36.980 --> 01:12:43.310
For someone who is
perhaps interested in kind

01:12:43.310 --> 01:12:47.210
of grasping the sense of
unfathomable or mystery

01:12:47.210 --> 01:12:53.240
or finding interest
in religion, do

01:12:53.240 --> 01:12:55.470
you have any words
of encouragement?

01:12:55.470 --> 01:12:58.118
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:58.118 --> 01:13:02.480
Or if it's not just coming
from sitting in a room

01:13:02.480 --> 01:13:06.570
and thinking on your own,
where does one find it?

01:13:06.570 --> 01:13:13.700
How did you find that sort of
encounter or understanding,

01:13:13.700 --> 01:13:15.990
if you can put it that way?

01:13:15.990 --> 01:13:20.960
- I haven't used conventional
methods, obviously.

01:13:20.960 --> 01:13:26.210
I think that-- what can I say?

01:13:26.210 --> 01:13:31.160
People come to it by unique
ways, I think, very often.

01:13:31.160 --> 01:13:32.870
If there's anything
that you consider

01:13:32.870 --> 01:13:37.090
to be overwhelmingly
beautiful or amazing,

01:13:37.090 --> 01:13:40.130
that gives you a taste of it.

01:13:40.130 --> 01:13:44.030
If I want to have a full-blown
religious experience that's

01:13:44.030 --> 01:13:51.090
as good as reading the psalms,
it's Scientific American.

01:13:51.090 --> 01:13:54.050
I love these
beautiful hypotheses

01:13:54.050 --> 01:13:57.800
about the beginnings of
things and the configuration

01:13:57.800 --> 01:13:59.320
of the universe and all this.

01:13:59.320 --> 01:14:01.880
It is so hyperbolic.

01:14:01.880 --> 01:14:05.630
I mean, the Earth is
not a speck of dust.

01:14:05.630 --> 01:14:07.790
And here we are,
looking at all this.

01:14:07.790 --> 01:14:10.080
It's absolutely amazing.

01:14:10.080 --> 01:14:13.070
I mean, that's my little
testimony to human beings

01:14:13.070 --> 01:14:17.960
as being totally
unaccountable creatures.

01:14:17.960 --> 01:14:25.100
But the things, the fact of
the materiality of things

01:14:25.100 --> 01:14:31.090
looked at closely disappear
under the gaze, all of that

01:14:31.090 --> 01:14:31.960
is very beautiful.

01:14:31.960 --> 01:14:34.720
And for me, it's
very theological.

01:14:38.320 --> 01:14:40.200
- Hi, my name is Bree.

01:14:40.200 --> 01:14:43.650
And as a reader,
in my experience,

01:14:43.650 --> 01:14:46.320
a lot of contemporary
literature tends

01:14:46.320 --> 01:14:49.380
to be characterized by
a sense of hopelessness.

01:14:49.380 --> 01:14:52.530
And as a lover of
stories, wanting

01:14:52.530 --> 01:14:56.400
to capture this really
powerful sense of awe and joy

01:14:56.400 --> 01:14:59.520
without it being seen as, like,
a lack of depth or something

01:14:59.520 --> 01:15:01.830
that's naive, I think
in your stories,

01:15:01.830 --> 01:15:03.960
you really capture
the balance of having

01:15:03.960 --> 01:15:08.850
this deep, real sense of reality
and this deep sense of sadness

01:15:08.850 --> 01:15:11.680
with this really real
experience of joy.

01:15:11.680 --> 01:15:14.580
And as a writer, I
guess, how do you

01:15:14.580 --> 01:15:16.830
strike that balance
between those two

01:15:16.830 --> 01:15:19.740
and have it be believable?

01:15:19.740 --> 01:15:22.020
And I guess, the follow-up
question would be too,

01:15:22.020 --> 01:15:24.390
like, what do you
see the role of hope

01:15:24.390 --> 01:15:27.980
in literature moving forward?

01:15:27.980 --> 01:15:30.940
- Well, I think that
it has to be authentic.

01:15:30.940 --> 01:15:32.840
You know what I mean?

01:15:32.840 --> 01:15:37.310
I don't think that you can
induce in yourself something

01:15:37.310 --> 01:15:38.900
you don't yourself feel.

01:15:38.900 --> 01:15:40.910
You can work towards
something you don't feel.

01:15:40.910 --> 01:15:44.390
That's always valuable.

01:15:44.390 --> 01:15:48.380
I think that finding the balance
between anything and anything

01:15:48.380 --> 01:15:52.850
else-- when you're writing,
every question is real.

01:15:52.850 --> 01:15:55.130
Every moment is
another question.

01:15:55.130 --> 01:15:56.280
How do I do this?

01:15:56.280 --> 01:15:57.800
How do I do this?

01:15:57.800 --> 01:16:01.520
There is no solution that's
external to the specific work

01:16:01.520 --> 01:16:02.900
that you are doing.

01:16:02.900 --> 01:16:05.990
I think that one of the
things that really helps

01:16:05.990 --> 01:16:11.750
is respect for your
characters, that you don't

01:16:11.750 --> 01:16:13.560
embarrass them or abuse them.

01:16:13.560 --> 01:16:16.250
Or you know what I mean?

01:16:16.250 --> 01:16:20.990
I think that maybe readers take
a certain amount of reassurance

01:16:20.990 --> 01:16:23.717
from the fact that they
are also not being abused.

01:16:23.717 --> 01:16:24.800
They're not being lied to.

01:16:27.550 --> 01:16:28.280
- Thank you.

01:16:28.280 --> 01:16:29.740
- You're welcome.

01:16:29.740 --> 01:16:30.240
- Hi, there.

01:16:30.240 --> 01:16:31.985
My name is Catherine.

01:16:31.985 --> 01:16:33.610
My question is, are
there ways that you

01:16:33.610 --> 01:16:35.440
would recommend to us
to better cultivate

01:16:35.440 --> 01:16:37.514
graciousness in our lives?

01:16:37.514 --> 01:16:38.680
- To cultivate graciousness?

01:16:38.680 --> 01:16:41.530
- Yeah.

01:16:41.530 --> 01:16:47.600
- Well, I mean, I so
admire the project.

01:16:47.600 --> 01:16:49.390
I mean, I think
that that would be

01:16:49.390 --> 01:16:51.850
the answer to so many problems.

01:16:51.850 --> 01:16:59.150
But you have to notice
it when you see it.

01:16:59.150 --> 01:17:02.060
You have to be aware that
you have an occasion where

01:17:02.060 --> 01:17:06.050
you yourself can enact it.

01:17:06.050 --> 01:17:08.930
I think one of the
things that we don't do--

01:17:08.930 --> 01:17:12.650
I talk about Calvin
and the human being

01:17:12.650 --> 01:17:14.630
on the stage with God
watching and so on.

01:17:14.630 --> 01:17:20.060
But we have, individually
in our own lives,

01:17:20.060 --> 01:17:25.930
the continuing possibility
of acting well;

01:17:25.930 --> 01:17:28.810
thinking not, what do I
need or what do I want,

01:17:28.810 --> 01:17:32.350
but what's gracious
in this moment.

01:17:32.350 --> 01:17:38.830
I think that's really the
discipline, to be aware of,

01:17:38.830 --> 01:17:43.510
in terms of the sort of whole
canvas of human dignity,

01:17:43.510 --> 01:17:45.670
how could I make a
decent account of myself

01:17:45.670 --> 01:17:46.630
in this moment?

01:17:46.630 --> 01:17:48.280
How can I do
something beautiful?

01:17:50.820 --> 01:17:53.009
That's what I would say.

01:17:53.009 --> 01:17:53.800
- Thanks very much.

01:17:57.680 --> 01:18:00.600
[MUSIC PLAYING]

01:18:00.600 --> 01:18:03.760
- Well, that was really
an inspiring conversation.

01:18:03.760 --> 01:18:07.110
